amptonshire, England","England":"England","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England","<Of Barton, Eccles, Lancashire, England>":"Barton, Lancashire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"<1424>–1520":"1424–1520","1424–1520":"1424–1520","1426–1473":"1426–1473","1428–Female":"1428–Deceased","1455–1480":"1455–1480","1400–1439":"1400–1439","1400–1481":"1400–1481","<1424>":"1424","1426":"1426","1424":"1424","1455":"1455","1400":"1400","1520":"1520","1473":"1473","1481":"1481","1480":"1480","1439":"1439","1428":"1428","Northampton, Northamptonshire, England":"Northampton, Northamptonshire, England","England":"England","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England","<Of Barton, Eccles, Lancashire, England>":"Barton, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Chauntrell","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English:  see  Cantrell  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Cantrell","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from Old French <i>canterelle</i>, <i>chanterelle</i>, a diminutive of <i>c(h)anteor</i> ‘singer’. Compare   Cantor  . It was used as an alternative name for Chantecler the cock in medieval French versions of the folk story of Reynard the Fox (<i>Le Roman de Renard</i>).","English: sometimes a variant of   Quintrell  .","English: occasionally, perhaps a habitational name from Cantrell in Devon, early recorded as <i>Canterhulle</i>, named from an unexplained first element + Old English <i>hyll</i> ‘hill’."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":31,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"When William John Chauntrell was born in 1424, in Barton, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom, his father, William Chauntrell Esquire, was 24 and his mother, Alice de Bold, was 24. He had at least 1 son with Lucy Booth. He died in 1520, in England, at the age of 96."},"et":{"<1424>–1520":"1424–1520","1424–1520":"1424–1520","1426–1473":"1426–1473","1428–Female":"1428–Surnud","1455–1480":"1455–1480","1400–1439":"1400–1439","1400–1481":"1400–1481","<1424>":"1424","1426":"1426","1424":"1424","1455":"1455","1400":"1400","1520":"1520","1473":"1473","1481":"1481","1480":"1480","1439":"1439","1428":"1428","Northampton, Northamptonshire, England":"Northampton, Northamptonshire, England","England":"England","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England","<Of Barton, Eccles, Lancashire, England>":"Barton, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"<1424>–1520":"1424–1520","1424–1520":"1424–1520","1426–147